  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Championing the Rights of Street Children in Kenya</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This is a research proposal to conduct a baseline survey of the number of street children going through the juvenile justice system in Kenya.  It arises from the applicant organisation&#x2019;s experience of the Kenyan justice system as it impacts on the estimated 250,000 street children in the country. Street children are involved in many different crimes, theft, drug trafficking, assault, trespass and property damage, and can also be criminalised by being arrested for &#x201C;vagrancy&#x201D;, itself  a crime.  Harassment by police, sexual and physical assault, and incarceration in adult gaols and remand centres are all commonplace. 
The project will focus on two regional cities, where the numbers of homeless children have increased dramatically since the 2007 violence.  The work will be undertaken by the Kenyan sister agency of the applicant, collaborating with other agencies and government departments.  It builds on evidence gained by a CLEAR (Christian Legal Education, Aid and Research) Intern who lived with the street children in 2009, and on its previous work with young people in schools and through the courts. Successful completion of this research is intended to lead to a larger project to support street children appropriately and to improve their treatment by the police and other officials.</narrative>
  </description>
